<subSubSection id="DBDD72F4A346AA533B5717B0F91BAD0B" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" type="comments">
<paragraph id="955E9B3E4CBFE68691956267BD0234AA" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="31CD0CFB0293AC53AEF9B01C8E13D86D" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName id="3001E1AF6BD22FED0971D04D6FC80AC2" authorityName="P. M. Peterson, Caldasia 31 (2): 279, f. 2 A-B" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Doell" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia bryophilus" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bryophilus">
<emphasis id="228AB4A2090DC7293CBE377C133054E5" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">Muhlenbergia bryophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="FABFB918D3B34DB8D147096ACB7DF47A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. cenchroides" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="cenchroides">
<emphasis id="0013A06BC309DF49165A3AEC65A953B0" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">M. cenchroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and can be separated from the latter in having anthers 0.5-0.7 mm long, the annual habit with culms (4-) 6-30 cm tall and sessile or inconspicuously pedicelled perfect spikelet associated with one (rarely two) staminate or sterile pedicelled spikelet (
<bibRefCitation id="1F75C7BADDFEBB2345B496173CBD6D62" author="Tovar, O" journalOrPublisher="Ruizia" pageId="60" pageNumber="183" pagination="1 - 480" refId="B59" refString="Tovar, O, 1993. Las Gramineas (Poaceae) del Peru. Ruizia 13: 1 - 480" title="Las Gramineas (Poaceae) del Peru." volume="13" year="1993">Tovar 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9274A0B9231E2DF13A4465B01CAD4A10" author="Giraldo-Canas, D" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="269 - 302" refId="B7" refString="Giraldo-Canas, D, Peterson, P, 2009. El genero Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae: Muhlenbergiinae) en Colombia. Caldasia 31: 269 - 302" title="El genero Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae: Muhlenbergiinae) en Colombia." volume="31" year="2009">
<normalizedToken id="FBFD39954B85835BDF56917DB1FC3E20" originalValue="Giraldo-Cañas">Giraldo-Canas</normalizedToken>
and Peterson 2009
</bibRefCitation>
). The central lemmatal awn length of the sessile or inconspicuously pedicelled spikelet was used by 
<bibRefCitation id="9D86AB3C3B8F4E6614986C45F4476C4B" author="Beetle, AA" journalOrPublisher=")" pageId="57" pageNumber="180" pagination="17 - 23" refId="B1" refString="Beetle, AA, 1948. The genus Aegopogon Humb. &amp; Bonpl. University of Wyoming Publications (Laramie, Wyo.) 13: 17 - 23" title="The genus Aegopogon Humb. &amp; Bonpl. University of Wyoming Publications (Laramie, Wyo." volume="13" year="1948">Beetle (1948)</bibRefCitation>
to differentiate between these two species but we found this measure to be completely overlapping. 
<taxonomicName id="608774A81F0AABF2ADA18B3E47977DF5" authorityName="P. M. Peterson, Caldasia 31 (2): 279, f. 2 A-B" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Doell" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia bryophilus" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bryophilus">
<emphasis id="C980971961EE225FB605A46EBEFBE937" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">Muhlenbergia bryophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to a single entry of 
<taxonomicName id="C08437DAD0BB499E56EE6AF2878EE127" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. uniseta" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="uniseta">
<emphasis id="4ABB116E687EB9BBC366033FBE0746EA" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">M. uniseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Peterson 24712) in our new analysis (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D51D1F6F0443E562BE455FB738E9EE0C" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A, B Maximum-likelihood tree inferred from combined plastid (ndhA intron, rps 16 - trnK, rps 16 intron, rps 3, and rpl 32 - trnL) and ITS sequences. Thick branches indicate posterior probabilities of 0.95 - 1; species in red occur in South America; scale bar = 2 %." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.114.28799.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/254042" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">1B</figureCitation>
). We have only a single marker (ITS) for 
<taxonomicName id="10097062AAC813C4988A140F41FDE727" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. bryophilus" order="Poales" pageId="14" pageNumber="137" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="bryophilus">
<emphasis id="57816B8E97D3FD74F37B64272567A85F" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="137">M. bryophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so its alignment may change with additional plastid markers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
